As a general rule, you shouldn&#39;t need `doNothing`, since mocks by default do &quot;nothing&quot; when their methods are called.  You would only need to write `doNothing` if you are working with a _spy_ instead of a _mock_.

In Mockito 1.x, you can write

    doNothing().when(yourSpyGoesHere).aa(any(B.class));

which effectively disables any call to `aa`.

The meaning of `any` was changed in Mockito 2, so you now need to write `nullable` instead of `any`.

    doNothing().when(yourSpyGoesHere).aa(nullable(B.class));

